While researching online safety and cybercrime, I was genuinely surprised by how widespread and advanced cyber threats have become, especially those targeting college students in India. I had always assumed that scams mainly affect less tech-savvy people, but I learned that students are actually a major target due to their frequent online activity, use of digital payments, and presence on social media. Fraudsters now use very convincing methods such as fake internship offers, phishing emails, cloned websites, and even impersonation through calls or messages. What shocked me the most was how quickly a small mistake—like clicking on an unknown link, scanning a random QR code, or sharing an OTP—can result in immediate financial loss, particularly through UPI transactions.

Another surprising aspect was how difficult it can be to identify these scams at first glance, as many fake platforms look almost identical to genuine ones. This made me realize that awareness and attention to detail are extremely important in today’s digital world.

As a result of this research, one habit I will personally change is becoming more cautious and mindful while using the internet. I will make it a rule to always verify links, check website authenticity, and avoid making any payments without proper confirmation. I will also ensure that I never share sensitive information like OTPs, passwords, or banking details with anyone. Adopting these practices will help me stay safer online and protect myself from potential cyber threats.